  'Meeting Notes: Discuss Encamp, timelines, next steps, etc.',
  '## **Project Scope and Resourcing**

The team clarified the project scope and adjusted roles to improve efficiency and accountability.

- **Bailey was assigned as the new account director for the NCAMP website project** to provide focused leadership and support for Nina, replacing the original lead who is stepping back (00:00)  
    - The shift aims to bring more hands-on management as the website work ramps up  
    - Nina continues to handle brand-related tasks, while Bailey focuses on project coordination and delivery  
    - This change addresses previous bottlenecks and unclear ownership in the workflow  
    - Introducing Bailey allows for better client communication and internal coordination  

- **The scope was narrowed to exclude copywriting and several design deliverables like PowerPoint and social media templates** after multiple out-of-scope requests and scope creep issues (01:40)  
    - NCAMP agreed to provide all website copy, with the internal copywriter delivering Google Docs for design  
    - The team will deliver Figma design files and two ebooks, plus finalize brand guidelines  
    - Additional requests will be pushed back or handled as separate work beyond current agreements  
    - This redefinition ensures proper resource allocation and prevents uncontrolled project growth  

## **Content Delivery and Timeline Management**

The team established clear content delivery deadlines and a timeline framework to meet critical milestones.

- **NCAMP committed to delivering all website copy and product assets by January 2nd to meet the January 12th board meeting deadline** (06:54)  
    - Only three pages of copy have been produced in six weeks, highlighting content delays  
    - Nina and Bailey emphasized that design approval must precede development to avoid rework  
    - A timeline with key milestones including copy delivery, design approval, development, testing, and content migration is being created to set realistic expectations  
    - This schedule will be presented to NCAMP with clear assumptions and boundaries to prevent scope creep  

- **The timeline will include assumptions such as limited revision rounds and no scope expansion beyond approved deliverables** to enforce discipline (10:59)  
    - Nina stressed the importance of defining how many revisions per page are acceptable to manage feedback flow  
    - The timeline will also cover template development for simpler pages like blogs, privacy notices, and terms  
    - Content migration from the existing WordPress site will be automated with Demir’s support, reducing manual tasks and speeding up delivery  
    - AI tools will assist in cleaning and formatting migrated content for faster turnaround  

## **Client Communication and Workflow Improvements**

Improving communication channels and workflows was prioritized to reduce delays and clarify expectations.

- **A Slack channel will be set up to enable real-time communication and faster feedback loops with NCAMP’s team** (15:58)  
    - This replaces slow email chains and long meeting lead times, which have delayed progress  
    - Bailey will handle introductions and ongoing communication to smooth collaboration  
    - The Slack channel will be the primary hub for updates, questions, and task status alongside Pulse for task tracking  
    - This change aims to accelerate approvals and reduce the typical one to two-week turnaround for responses  

- **Weekly meetings with the copywriter Kylie have fallen off due to slow progress on copy and unclear priorities** (18:57)  
    - Kylie’s requests for out-of-scope deliverables caused confusion and required firm pushback to reset expectations  
    - Bailey and Nina clarified that only two ebooks and the website are in scope, with no additional templates or materials  
    - Kylie’s inconsistent adherence to original copy and formatting standards added quality control challenges  
    - This communication reset was crucial to align all parties on project boundaries and deliverables  

## **Quality Control and Design Finalization**

The team reinforced brand guidelines and quality checks to avoid rework and maintain consistency.

- **Brand guidelines are finalized and frozen to prevent ongoing changes that delay design and QA** (16:37)  
    - Nina highlighted that repeated modifications forced multiple rounds of design and quality assessments  
    - Lou and Georgia have been involved in thorough quality checks to ensure compliance with brand standards  
    - This freeze enables the design team to focus on website pages and ebook layouts without shifting requirements  
    - The final guidelines serve as a baseline for all creative assets to maintain consistency across deliverables  

- **AI-assisted content generation is used cautiously due to quality issues and client reluctance** (21:40)  
    - Bailey noted that although AI can speed up copywriting, inconsistent formatting and errors require significant manual fixes  
    - The client prefers human-written copy but struggles with timely delivery, creating a tension between quality and speed  
    - Clear communication with the client about these trade-offs is necessary to set realistic expectations  
    - The team remains open to AI tools but will maintain rigorous review processes to uphold standards  

## **Next Steps and Deliverable Management**

Concrete plans were set to finalize deliverables and ensure smooth project handoff.

- **Nina will draft a high-level timeline and assumptions document using an existing kitchen sink template, targeting delivery by tomorrow** (23:25)  
    - The template provides a ready-made structure for milestones and presentation styles, speeding up preparation  
    - The timeline will incorporate phased content delivery assumptions, allowing for progressive design and development  
    - Bailey will coordinate sharing the timeline and team introductions via Slack to facilitate immediate feedback  
    - This documentation will serve as the foundation for managing client expectations and internal workflows  

- **Bailey will manage ongoing communications and help transition leadership as the original project lead reduces involvement** (15:58)  
    - The team anticipates smoother progress with more hands involved and clearer accountability  
    - Emphasis remains on limiting scope creep and ensuring timely delivery of copy, design, and development milestones  
    - Continuous monitoring of client responsiveness and quality will be necessary to maintain momentum  
    - The approach aims to deliver the website and ebooks on schedule for the January 12th board meeting with minimal surprises',
